ote": "In Sharma's Kriya-Yoga, tapas is the inner fire of discipline that purifies and generates creative energy. The repeated 'abhyatapat' (heated) symbolizes the yogic practice of generating inner heat (tapas) to manifest reality.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.1.1", "gopa_1.1.2", "gopa_1.1.3", "gopa_1.1.5", "gopa_1.1.6", "gopa_1.1.7", "gopa_1.1.8", "gopa_1.1.10", "gopa_1.1.11", "gopa_1.1.12"]}, {"teaching": "The great utterances (mahavyahrtis) encapsulate the essence of the Vedas and can substitute for them.", "lens_note": "Sharma would see this as the power of mantra and sound vibration (nada) in Kriya-Yoga. The mahavyahrtis are condensed forms of cosmic energy that can be used in meditation to access the entire Veda.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.1.5", "gopa_1.1.6", "gopa_1.1.8", "gopa_1.1.10", "gopa_1.1.11"]}, {"teaching": "The first sacrifice was performed by Brahman with the gods as priests, establishing the ritual order.", "lens_note": "In Kriya-Yoga, sacrifice (yajna) is internalized as the offering of breath and awareness. The external ritual mirrors the inner sacrifice of ego and desires.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.1.13"]}, {"teaching": "Knowledge of this creation leads to spiritual attainment and protection.", "lens_note": "Sharma emphasizes that knowing the cosmic process through direct experience (as in Kriya-Yoga) empowers the practitioner. The repeated phrase 'ya evam veda' (who knows thus) underscores the transformative power of knowledge.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.1.3", "gopa_1.1.4", "gopa_1.1.5", "gopa_1.1.6", "gopa_1.1.8", "gopa_1.1.9", "gopa_1.1.10", "gopa_1.1.11"]}], "_provenance": {"purana": "Gopatha Brahmana", "chapter_label": "Chapter 0 (part 1)", "seq_start": 1, "seq_end": 80, "chunk_ids": ["gopatha-0-1", "gopatha-0-2", "gopatha-0-3", "gopatha-0-4", "gopatha-0-5", "gopatha-0-6", "gopatha-0-7", "gopatha-0-8", "gopatha-0-9", "gopatha-0-10", "gopatha-0-11", "gopatha-0-12", "gopatha-0-13", "gopatha-0-14", "gopatha-0-15", "gopatha-0-16", "gopatha-0-1