e of the brahmacarin, including a dialogue with King Janamejaya.", "characters": ["Savitri", "Savitā", "Agni", "Vāyu", "Āditya", "Candramā", "Pṛthivī", "Antarikṣa", "Dyauḥ", "Brahmacārī", "Janamejaya", "Dakṣiṇāgni", "Āhavanīya", "Dantāvala Dhaumra", "Vasiṣṭha", "Viśvāmitra", "Jamadagni", "Gautama", "Bharadvāja", "Śiva", "Mṛtyu"], "timeline_note": "Mythical time; the dialogue with Janamejaya is set in the context of his hunting expedition.", "comic_potential": "Low; the text is ritualistic and philosophical."}, "teachings": [{"teaching": "The Savitri mantra is the mother of the Vedas; understanding its three padas leads to immortality and the attainment of all desires.", "lens_note": "In Sharma's Kriya-Yoga, this corresponds to the integration of the three levels of consciousness (waking, dreaming, deep sleep) into the fourth (turiya), which is the realization of the Self as the source of all.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.1.34", "gopa_1.1.35", "gopa_1.1.36", "gopa_1.1.37", "gopa_1.1.38"]}, {"teaching": "The brahmacarin should offer fire oblations daily, beg for alms, and avoid sexual contact; by doing so, he conquers death and attains heavenly worlds.", "lens_note": "Sharma emphasizes that brahmacarya is not mere celibacy but the channeling of vital energy upward through the sushumna nadi, leading to spiritual awakening.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.2", "gopa_1.2.3", "gopa_1.2.4", "gopa_1.2.6"]}, {"teaching": "The brahmacarin should not sleep on a high bed, sing, dance, run, or spit; these actions lead to negative consequences.", "lens_note": "These rules are external aids to internal discipline; in Kriya-Yoga, they correspond to yama and niyama, which purify the mind and body for meditation.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.7"]}, {"teaching": "The fires Dakshinagni and Ahavaniya teach Janamejaya that brahmacarya is the highest virtue and the means to attain the heavenly world.", "lens_note": "This dialogue illustrates that true knowledge comes from direct experience and guidance from enlightened beings, a key principle in the guru-shishya tradition.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.5"]}], "_provenance": {"purana": "Gopatha Brahmana", "chapter_label": "Chapter 0 (part 3)", "seq_start": 161, "seq_end": 240, "chunk_ids": ["gopatha-0-161", "gopatha-0-162", "gopatha-0-163", "gopatha-0-164", "gopatha-0-165", "gopatha-0-166", "gopatha-0-167", "gopatha-0-168", "gopatha-0-169", "gopatha-0-170", "gopatha-0-171", "gopatha-0-172", "gopatha-0-173", "gopatha-0-174", "gopatha-0-175", "gopatha-0-176", "gopatha-0-177", "gopatha-0-178", "gopatha-0-179", "gopatha-0-180", "gopatha-0-181", "gopatha-0-182", "gopatha-0-183", "gopatha-0-184", "gopatha-0-185", "gopatha-0-186", "gopatha-0-187", "gopatha-0-188", "gopatha-0-189", "gopatha-0-190", "gopatha-0-191", "gopatha-0-192", "gopatha-0-193", "gopatha-0-194", "gopatha-0-195", "gopatha-0-196", "gopatha-0-197", "gopatha-0-198", "gopatha-0-199", "gopatha-0-200", "gopatha-0-201", "gopatha-0-202", "gopatha-0-203", "gopatha-0-204", "gopatha-0-205", "gopatha-0-206", "gopatha-0-207", "gopatha-0-208", "gopatha-0-209", "gopatha-0-210", "gopatha-0-211", "gopatha-0-212", "gopatha-0-213", "gopatha-0-214", "gopatha-0-215", "gopatha-0-216", "gopatha-0-217", "gopatha-0-218", "gopatha-0-219", "gopatha-0-220", "gopatha-0-221", "gopatha-0-222", "gopatha-0-223", "gopatha-0-224", "gopatha-0-225", "gopatha-0-226", "gopatha-0-227", "gopatha-0-228", "gopatha-0-229", "gopatha-0-230", "gopatha-0-231", "gopatha-0-232", "gopatha-0-233", "gopatha-0-234", "gopatha-0-235", "gopatha-0-236", "gopatha-0-237", "gopatha-0-238", "gopatha-0-239", "gopatha-0-240"], "provider": "deepseek", "model": "deepseek-chat", "lens_applied": true, "salvaged": false, "pruned_invalid_nodes": false}}
{"chapter_summary": "This chapter from the Gopatha Brahmana discusses the nature of the sacrifice (yajña) as having four feet (catuṣpād), correlating with the four worlds, four deities, four Vedas, and four priestly functions. It narrates the story of Vicārī Kābandhi, who questions the priests about the essence of their roles, leading to the revelation that the Hotr is speech, the Adhvaryu is prāṇa and apāna, the Udgātr is sight, and the Brahmā is mind. The chapter also describes the origin of the Brahmaudana, the horse sacrifice, and the importance of the Atharvaṅgiras priests. It emphasizes that the Brahmā priest, as the mind of the sacrifice, is essential for its completion, and that without him the sacrifice is incomplete.", "entities": [{"name": "Prajāpati", "kind": "deity", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.15", "gopa_1.2.16", "gopa_1.2.18", "gopa_1.2.24", "gopa_1.3.2"]}, {"name": "Aditi", "kind": "deity", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.15"]}, {"name": "Ādityas", "kind": "deity", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.15"]}, {"name": "Agni", "kind": "deity", "aliases": ["Vaiśvānara", "Jātavedas"], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.15", "gopa_1.2.16", "gopa_1.2.18", "gopa_1.2.20", "gopa_1.2.21", "gopa_1.2.22", "gopa_1.2.23"]}, {"name": "Vāyu", "kind": "deity", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"name": "Candramā", "kind": "deity", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"name": "Āditya", "kind": "deity", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"name": "Indra", "kind": "deity", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.19", "gopa_1.2.21"]}, {"name": "Vicārī Kābandhi", "kind": "sage", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.10"]}, {"name": "Kabandha Atharvaṇa", "kind": "sage", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.10"]}, {"name": "Māndhātṛ Yauvanāśva", "kind": "king", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.10"]}, {"name": "Śvetaketu Āruṇeya", "kind":