addhā", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.14"]}, {"name": "Ātmā", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.14"]}, {"name": "Vāc", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11", "gopa_1.2.18", "gopa_1.3.2"]}, {"name": "Mana", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11", "gopa_1.3.2"]}, {"name": "Prāṇa", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11", "gopa_1.2.22"]}, {"name": "Apāna", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11"]}, {"name": "Cakṣus", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11", "gopa_1.2.22"]}, {"name": "Aśva", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.18", "gopa_1.2.20", "gopa_1.2.21"]}, {"name": "Ratha", "kind": "concept", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.21"]}, {"name": "Kurukṣetra", "kind": "place", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.10"]}, {"name": "Pṛthivī", "kind": "place", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"name": "Antarikṣa", "kind": "place", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"name": "Dyaur", "kind": "place", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"name": "Āpa", "kind": "place", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"name": "Samudra", "kind": "place", "aliases": [], "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.10"]}], "relationships": [{"src": "Brahmā", "rel": "is", "dst": "Mana", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11"]}, {"src": "Hotr", "rel": "is", "dst": "Vāc", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11"]}, {"src": "Adhvaryu", "rel": "is", "dst": "Prāṇa and Apāna", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11"]}, {"src": "Udgātr", "rel": "is", "dst": "Cakṣus", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11"]}, {"src": "Agni Vaiśvānara", "rel": "becomes", "dst": "Aśva", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.20"]}, {"src": "Indra", "rel": "becomes", "dst": "Brahmaveda", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.19"]}, {"src": "Bhṛgu and Aṅgiras", "rel": "are", "dst": "Brahmā", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.22"]}, {"src": "Prajāpati", "rel": "creates", "dst": "Brahmaudana", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"src": "Aditi", "rel": "cooks", "dst": "Odana", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.15"]}, {"src": "Ādityas", "rel": "born from", "dst": "Aditi", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.15"]}, {"src": "Vicārī Kābandhi", "rel": "questions", "dst": "Ṛtvij", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.10"]}, {"src": "Śvetaketu", "rel": "states", "dst": "Brahmā is half of sacrifice", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.3.3"]}], "story": {"title": "The Four-Footed Sacrifice and the Role of the Brahmā", "arc": "Exposition of the Yajña as having four feet, correlating with worlds, deities, Vedas, and priests; the story of Vicārī Kābandhi; the horse sacrifice; the importance of the Brahmā priest.", "characters": ["Prajāpati", "Aditi", "Ādityas", "Agni", "Vāyu", "Candramā", "Āditya", "Indra", "Vicārī Kābandhi", "Kabandha Atharvaṇa", "Māndhātṛ Yauvanāśva", "Śvetaketu Āruṇeya", "Bhṛgu", "Aṅgiras", "Atharvā", "Śaṃyu Ātharvaṇa"], "timeline_note": "Mythological time; the events are set in the primordial period of creation and the establishment of sacrifice.", "comic_potential": "The dialogue between Vicārī Kābandhi and the priests, where the priests are stumped and then enlightened, has humorous potential. Also, the horse that refuses to be tamed by the first three Vedas but is calmed by the Atharvaṇa priest."}, "teachings": [{"teaching": "The sacrifice (yajña) has four feet: the four worlds, four deities, four Vedas, and four priestly functions.", "lens_note": "Sharma's Kriya-Yoga would see this as a map of the inner sacrifice: the four feet correspond to the four levels of consciousness (waking, dreaming, deep sleep, and turīya) and the four functions of the mind (sensory, motor, cognitive, and intuitive).", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.9", "gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"teaching": "The Hotr is speech (vāc), the Adhvaryu is prāṇa and apāna, the Udgātr is sight (cakṣus), and the Brahmā is mind (manas).", "lens_note": "Sharma would interpret this as the identification of the external priestly functions with internal yogic processes: speech corresponds to mantra repetition, prāṇa-apāna to breath control, sight to concentration, and mind to meditation.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.11"]}, {"teaching": "The Brahmā priest is the mind of the sacrifice; without him, the sacrifice is incomplete and goes astray.", "lens_note": "This emphasizes the primacy of inner awareness (mind) in any ritual. Sharma would stress that external actions without inner mindfulness are ineffective.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.3.2", "gopa_1.3.3"]}, {"teaching": "The horse (aśva) is a form of Agni Vaiśvānara; it is tamed by the Atharvaṇa priest using the appropriate hymns.", "lens_note": "The horse symbolizes the restless senses or life-force. Taming it represents mastery over the senses through the knowledge of the Atharvaveda (Brahmaveda).", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.18", "gopa_1.2.20", "gopa_1.2.21"]}, {"teaching": "The Brahmaudana (rice offering to Brahmā) is the source of the four worlds, four deities, four Vedas, and four priestly functions.", "lens_note": "This teaching points to the unity behind diversity. Sharma would see the Brahmaudana as the primordial creative energy (ojas) that manifests as the entire cosmos and the Vedic tradition.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.16"]}, {"teaching": "The Sāṃtapana Agni is the Brāhmaṇa who has undergone the sacraments; without fire (agnihotra), a Brāhmaṇa is like a clod in a pot, unfit for offerings.", "lens_note": "Sharma would interpret this as the necessity of inner fire (tapas) and discipline. The sacraments are external aids to kindle the inner fire.", "verse_ranges": ["gopa_1.2.22", "gopa_1.2.23"]}, {"teaching": "The Brahmā priest should be chosen from among the Atharvaṅgiras; otherwise, the sacrifice is diminished.", "lens_note": "This underscores the importance of the Brahmaveda (Atharvaveda) as the knowledge that integrates 